Something a little different…Astrophotography Timelapse 

Time lapse video experiment (from a few years back) with a 350 shot sequence taken of the North Star, Polaris over Milton, Georgia

Assembled using Lightroom and LRTimelapse 

Imaging: 
Canon EOS 6D
Canon EF 24-70mm f/2.8L II USM 
ISO1600, 24mm, f/2.8, 12.0 sec

350 frames taken over 76 minutes - 12 seconds each at 1 sec intervals ... while the camera was aimed toward Polaris capturing Earth’s rotation ... The faint lighter area to the right is that from the north-reaching arc of the Milky Way seen near Constellation Cygnus

The unique and iconic look of the Lockheed T-33 “Shooting Star” (originally built by Lockheed Aeronautical Systems, now Lockheed-Martin @lockheedmartin ). Designed by the original Skunkworks genius Clarence “Kelly” Johnson - aeronautical engineer and father of the achievements like the SR-71 Blackbird and the U-2 DragonLady Spy planes. The T-33 served as a tactical Training jet for fighter pilots who were already qualified in propeller aircraft. Its history dates back to the late 1940s

Swipe ⏪ Another from #WOWAirshow and a piece of major aviation history — Gregory W Colyer of @acemakeraviation “Gregory W Colyer/Ace Maker Airshows”
The unique and iconic look of the Lockheed T-33 “Shooting Star” (originally built by Lockheed Aeronautical Systems, now Lockheed-Martin @lockheedmartin ). Designed by the original Skunkworks genius Clarence “Kelly” Johnson - aeronautical engineer and father of the achievements like the SR-71 Blackbird and the U-2 DragonLady Spy planes. The T-33 served as a tactical Training jet for fighter pilots who were already qualified in propeller aircraft. Its history dates back to the late 1940s

Boeing GBU-31: A Mk84 bomb fitted with a JDAM kit… it’s a basic “gravity bomb” outfitted with a “fin package” and guidance system that converts it to a precision guided munition (GPS guided) Compatible with almost 2 dozen allied airframes including the newer more advance 5th generation fighters like the F-35 Lightning II.
